I work for a state-level union that represents all K-12 teachers and staff, all state/county/municipal workers, and all higher ed faculty/academic staff/non-academic staff, tasked with increasing our HE membership, assisting with member rights cases, coordinating HE-related political activity, improving our data management processes, and a bunch more.
Income - context:
The salary is good for the small "industry" and area, but the benefits are exceptional even for union staff jobs, where employers are usually trying to live their values and the workers usually have their own union.

I have a defined-benefit retirement plan with annual COLA offered by our national affiliate. I have a separate 401(k) that my employer contributes a fixed dollar amount to every year that's more than 5% of my gross (which is more than I ever expected to save from my contribution *plus* employer matching). I have the best health insurance I've ever heard of with the premium fully paid and $3500 a year in FSA/HRA contributions. We have real, substantial PTO and more staff actually taking it than I've ever seen at a union. They paid my relocation from across the country, which is normally unheard-of except for national union jobs at the management level. Plus a collective bargaining agreement with just cause, progressive discipline, representation, and all the other stuff you don't know you need until you don't have it. This is the kind of security everyone should and *could* have. Reminds me what we're fighting for every day I go to work.
